explanation:
For assessing whether code in OS_ConsoleTask_Entry is dead (i.e. executed but removable without changing program behaviour) the analyzer must know the semantics and side-effects of the following symbols:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Determines whether the initial if-body ever executes (return conditions) and its side effects (token allocation/refcounting). If it never succeeds the body is never executed; if it has side effects removal could change behaviour.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Releases the token at function end; its side effects (refcount decrement/cleanup) affect global state and thus removal could change behaviour.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Used (directly or via macros) to map token→index; needed to understand how token is translated to a table index and whether the lookup can fail or have side effects.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro used to obtain local from OS_impl_console_table and token. Necessary to know how 'local' is derived and whether the lookup does additional checks/side effects.
- OS_impl_console_table: The object table from which local is retrieved; needed to know table lifetime/contents and whether retrieval is meaningful (affects whether subsequent operations are effective).
- OS_impl_console_internal_record_t: Definition of the record type (especially the data_sem member) to see what sem_wait operates on and whether removing the access changes behaviour.
- OS_ConsoleOutput_Impl: Called inside the loop; must know its observable side effects (I/O, state changes). If it has no observable effect removal might be dead, otherwise not.
- sem_wait: Blocking semantics and return behaviour are required to understand control flow (thread blocking vs busy behaviour) and whether removing the wait or its caller affects program timing/behaviour.
- OS_SharedGlobalVars: The GlobalState value controls loop exit; you must know who/when updates it to decide if the loop actually iterates or terminates, which affects whether the body is meaningful.
- OS_SHUTDOWN_MAGIC_NUMBER: The sentinel compared to GlobalState; needed to interpret the loop condition precisely.
- OS_VoidPtrValueWrapper_t: Type/union layout (how opaque_arg maps to id) is required to verify that local_arg.id correctly encodes the object id used by OS_ObjectIdGetById.
- OS_SUCCESS: Return code checked from OS_ObjectIdGetById; needed to know which return value allows body execution.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT: Lock mode argument to OS_ObjectIdGetById — its semantics may affect token acquisition/refcount behaviour and therefore observable effects.
- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONSOLE: Object-type argument to OS_ObjectIdGetById — needed to know which table/objects are examined; affects whether lookup succeeds and has side effects.
- OS_object_token_t: Token type used throughout (passed to lookup/release and to OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET); its contents and lifetime semantics are necessary to assess side effects and removability.

These symbols together let an analyst determine (1) whether the if-body and while-loop can ever execute, (2) whether calls inside the loop (OS_ConsoleOutput_Impl and sem_wait) perform observable actions or only local/no-op work, and (3) whether token acquisition/release manipulate global state. That information is required to decide if any executed operations are actually dead code under the MISRA dead-code definition.
